<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="158" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,607,1101]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,607,632]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
From the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scoble" authorityYear="1983" box="[503,662,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Simplimorpha">
<emphasis box="[503,662,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Simplimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoare" authorityYear="2000" box="[677,817,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Roscidotoga">
<emphasis box="[677,817,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Roscidotoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the presence of triangular silver mark on the costa of forewing, three distal veins of forewing (two in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scoble" authorityYear="1983" box="[776,934,644,668]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[776,934,644,668]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Simplimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), simply shaped, triangular valva in the male genitalia (valva with a ventral lobe in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scoble" authorityYear="1983" box="[598,757,680,704]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[598,757,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Simplimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the broad anterior apophyses in the female genitalia (anterior apophyses slender in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scoble" authorityYear="1983" box="[516,675,716,740]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[516,675,716,740]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Simplimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoare" authorityYear="2000" box="[704,844,716,740]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Roscidotoga">
<emphasis box="[704,844,716,740]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Roscidotoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also distinctive because it feeds on 
<taxonomicName box="[1316,1436,716,741]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Oxalidales</taxonomicName>
(Eurosids I / Fabids) and is distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[620,726,751,776]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Australia</collectingCountry>
, compared to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scoble" authorityYear="1983" box="[1038,1197,752,776]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Simplimorpha">
<emphasis box="[1038,1197,752,776]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Simplimorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that occurs in Africa and Mediterranean and feeds on 
<taxonomicName box="[517,639,788,813]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="order">Sapindales</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[653,825,788,813]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Magnoliopsida" rank="family">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,607,1101]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
From 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[269,435,824,848]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[269,435,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, s.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoare" authorityYear="2000" box="[500,640,824,848]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Roscidotoga">
<emphasis box="[500,640,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Roscidotoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the presence of three distal veins (four in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[1253,1419,824,848]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[1253,1419,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), absence of an anal loop in the forewing (present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[758,924,860,884]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[758,924,860,884]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), two distal veins of the hindwing (three in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,317,896,920]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[151,317,896,920]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the simple-shaped, generally triangular valva (in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[986,1153,896,920]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[986,1153,896,920]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
valva is very elaborate basally, see 
<figureCitation box="[288,426,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–49" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1329,1351]" captionText="FIGURES 1–49. Details of genitalia morphology of Simplimorpha Scoble, 1983 (sensu lato). 1–6, tegumen: 1, S. promissa (modified after van Nieukerken 1986); 2, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 3, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 4, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 5, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD707; 6, S. kailai, Satipo, Peru, slide AD935; 7–12, tegumen and vinculum: 7, S. promissa (modified after van Nieukerken 1986); 8, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 9, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 10, S. sapphiripes (modified after Hoare 2000); 11, S. kailai, Satipo, Peru, slide AD935; 12, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD707; 13–19, valva: 13, S. promissa (modified after van Nieukerken 1986); 14, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 15, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 16, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 17, S. sapphiripes (modified after Hoare 2000: Fig. 19); 18, S. kailai, Satipo, Peru, slide AD935; 19, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD707; 20–25, transtilla: 20, S. promissa, the Crimea, Europe, slide AD938; 21, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 22, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 23, S. sapphiripes (modified after Hoare 2000); 24, S. kailai, Satipo, Peru, slide AD935; 25, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD707; 26–37, phallus and cathrema: 26, S. promissa, the Crimea, Europe, slide AD938; 27, 28, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 29, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 30, S. lamingtonia (modified after van Nieukerken et al. 2011); 31, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 32, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 33, S. sapphiripes (modified after Hoare 2000); 34, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD707; 35, S. nielseni, Lago Lacar, Argentina, slide RA621; 36, 37, S. kailai, Satipo, Peru, slide AD935; 38–49, details of female genitalia: 38, 39, S. promissa (modified after Laštůvka &amp; Laštůvka 1997); 40, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 41, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 42, S. sapphiripes (modified after Hoare 2000); 43, S. callicomae (modified after Hoare 2000); 44, S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 45, 46, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD709; 47, S. sapphirella, Cauquenes, Chile, slide RA594; 48, S. nielseni, Hua-Hum, Argentina, slide RA619; 49, S. cercaria, Osorno, Chile, slide AD709." pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Figs. 18, 19</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stonis &amp; Diškus &amp; Remeikis &amp; Solis" authorityYear="2018" box="[447,613,932,956]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="180" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Myrtinepticula">
<emphasis box="[447,613,932,956]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Myrtinepticula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in South America. The constituent species feed on 
<taxonomicName box="[1285,1385,932,957]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Myrtales</taxonomicName>
(i.e. Eurosids II / Malvids), while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoare" authorityYear="2000" box="[480,620,968,992]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Simplimorpha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="179" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Roscidotoga">
<emphasis box="[480,620,968,992]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Roscidotoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species feed on 
<taxonomicName box="[805,925,967,992]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Oxalidales</taxonomicName>
(Eurosids I / Fabids). See also Discussion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,607,1101]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
Remarks. Description was provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hoare, R. J. B." box="[641,778,1004,1028]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" pagination="289 - 317" refId="ref9617" refString="Hoare, R. J. B. (2000) A new genus of primitive Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) from eastern Australia, with a revised diagnosis of nepticulid subfamilies. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 128 (3), 289 - 317. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2000. tb 00165. x" type="journal article" year="2000">Hoare 2000</bibRefCitation>
: 293, 294. Larvae are leaf miners (
<figureCitation box="[1165,1246,1004,1029]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–64" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1847,1869]" captionTargetBox="[178,1379,225,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1384,221,1812]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–64. Simplimorpha Scoble, 1983 (sensu lato). 58–61, examples of leaf mines: 58, S. nielseni, Hua-Hum, Argentina, ZMUC; 59, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 60, S. promissa, Crimea, Europe, LEU; 61, S. sapphiripes, S. callicomae and S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 62, distribution map; 63, 64, adult of S. promissa (Staudinger, 1870), currently the only Simplimorpha species known from the Northern Hemisphere (courtesy of Peter Buchner, Schwarzau am Steinfeld, Austria). Note: the plant taxa names follow APG IV (2016) and Stevens (2017)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609737/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Fig. 61</figureCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName box="[1291,1436,1004,1029]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cunoniaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cunoniaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1816" box="[203,377,1039,1064]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Elaeocarpaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Elaeocarpaceae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority=", Fabids" authorityName="Fabids" box="[396,610,1039,1064]" class="Magnoliopsida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Oxalidales" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="order">Oxalidales, Fabids</taxonomicName>
or =Eurosids I). Currently the subgenus is comprised of four species, distributed in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[393,499,1076,1101]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Australia</collectingCountry>
, including 
<collectingRegion box="[622,729,1076,1101]" country="Australia" name="Tasmania" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Tasmania</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hoare, R. J. B." box="[744,880,1076,1100]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" pagination="289 - 317" refId="ref9617" refString="Hoare, R. J. B. (2000) A new genus of primitive Nepticulidae (Lepidoptera) from eastern Australia, with a revised diagnosis of nepticulid subfamilies. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 128 (3), 289 - 317. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2000. tb 00165. x" type="journal article" year="2000">Hoare 2000</bibRefCitation>
, van 
<bibRefCitation author="Nieukerken, E. J. van &amp; Berg, C. van den &amp; Hoare, R. J. B." box="[938,1196,1076,1101]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" pagination="193 - 201" refId="ref9983" refString="Nieukerken, E. J. van, Berg, C. van den &amp; Hoare, R. J. B. (2011) A new species of the endemic Australian genus Roscidotoga Hoare from rainforests in southern Queensland (Lepidoptera: Nepticulidae). Tijdschrift voor Entomologie, 154, 193 - 201. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 004074912 X 13397496981508" type="journal article" year="2011">
Nieukerken 
<emphasis box="[1076,1132,1076,1100]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1218,1303,1076,1101]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–64" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1847,1869]" captionTargetBox="[178,1379,225,1805]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[176,1384,221,1812]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 58–64. Simplimorpha Scoble, 1983 (sensu lato). 58–61, examples of leaf mines: 58, S. nielseni, Hua-Hum, Argentina, ZMUC; 59, S. lanceifoliella (modified after Vári 1955); 60, S. promissa, Crimea, Europe, LEU; 61, S. sapphiripes, S. callicomae and S. eucryphiae (modified after Hoare 2000); 62, distribution map; 63, 64, adult of S. promissa (Staudinger, 1870), currently the only Simplimorpha species known from the Northern Hemisphere (courtesy of Peter Buchner, Schwarzau am Steinfeld, Austria). Note: the plant taxa names follow APG IV (2016) and Stevens (2017)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2609737/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
